{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413301"},"attributes":{"position":14,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:05:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:05:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2049"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503606"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:04:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:04:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2049"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2049"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.08,0.16,0.04,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54332"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2049"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39840"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11090"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41931"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54332"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man is brought to hospital via ambulance after a motor vehicle accident in which he sustained mild injuries suitable for outpatient treatment. On further history, he admits to having consumed significant amounts of alcohol immediately before the accident. He admits that his drinking habits have had a significant impact on his friendships, and that he is currently unemployed after being fired from his last job due to intoxication. He states that he has always had a difficult relationship with alcohol, and has tried several times to quit but with no success. His alcohol intake has been steadily increasing, and he now consumes approximately 15 standard drinks per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe takes no other medications or recreational drugs, and is otherwise healthy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the most appropriate pharmacological intervention to reduce this patient\u0027s impulse to drink?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acamprosate","Diazepam","Disulfiram","Naloxone","Naltrexone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient clearly has moderate to severe alcohol use disorder. He meets at least five of the DSM-5 criteria for alcohol use disorder. In patients who are currently continuing to drink, naltrexone is the most appropriate pharmacological intervention. \u003Cstrong\u003ENaltrexone\u003C/strong\u003E is a long-acting opioid inhibitor, and can decrease the sensation of the \u0022reward pathway\u0022 associated with alcohol, decreasing the patient\u0027s impulse to drink. Caution should be taken in moderate to severe hepatic impairment. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcamprosate\u003C/strong\u003E is effective in maintaining abstinence, however it is not as effective at helping patients quit. Its primary effects are relieving symptoms of abstinence and withdrawal, and so is primarily used in patients currently abstaining from alcohol. There are also adherence issues due to three time daily dosing and large physical size of tablets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for use in patients going through active withdrawal from alcohol. Though this patient may experience withdrawal symptoms if he does decide to quit he does not currently require diazepam. However, he should be alerted to the symptoms and risks of alcohol withdrawal and the possibility of a medically supervised withdrawal should be discussed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisulfiram\u003C/strong\u003E may help patients maintain abstinence, as it causes significant adverse effects when taken with alcohol. However, it is not indicated in patients who are currently drinking due to these adverse effects, and it is preferably to quit using other interventions before using disulfiram if deemed necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaloxone\u003C/strong\u003E is a short-acting opioid antagonist. It has no role in the treatment of alcohol use disorder, unlike naltrexone, as it is metabolised too quickly to be helpful in this application.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Naltrexone is a long-acting opioid inhibitor, and can decrease the sensation of the \u0022reward pathway\u0022 associated with alcohol, decreasing the patient\u0027s impulse to drink."],"references":["Jonas DE, Amick HR, Feltner C, Bobashev G, Thomas K, Wines R, Kim MM, Shanahan E, Gass CE, Rowe CJ, Garbutt JC. Pharmacotherapy for adults with alcohol use disorders in outpatient settings: a systematic review and meta-analysis. JAMA. 2014 May 14;311(18):1889-900. doi: 10.1001/jama.2014.3628. PMID: 24825644.","DSM-5 criteria for alcohol use disorder: https://cchealth.org/aod/pdf/DSM-5%20Diagnosis%20Reference%20Guide.pdf","Demirkol A, Conigrave K, Haber P. Problem drinking: Management in general practice. Australian family physician. 2011 Aug;40(8):576-82."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39840"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2049"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39840"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T09:30:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T20:44:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2049"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54332"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"sel